@realmoney Jan 08, 2020 | 03:25 PM EST DOUG KASS Staying Real As the today's trading day comes to a close, it is apparent that, like the 1997 Long Boom paradigm expressed in a column in Wired Magazine during the dot.com bubble -- the current market is

similarly viewed as in its own, new liquidity-based paradigm. No longer is the market hostage to the real economy or sales and profit growth - stuff I have spent four decades analyzing. Instead, liquidity is seen as an overriding influence - actually it has become the

sine quo non. As such, historical valuations become increasingly irrelevant and price momentum is the lodestar. There are many that are willing to play this game of musical chairs. I salute you - but that approach is not in my investing "DNA." I am not willing - as I must admit

to not having the conviction (in either direction) with knowledge that, in the fullness of time, buying high and selling higher will ultimately come to a brutal end. Equally important (and honestly), I currently don't have a real notion what to even look for as a signpost.

Accordingly, I have materially reduced my gross and net exposure today and I plan to stay in that state of suspended animation for a while. This means, while I will be trading and investing actively (as usual), I will be doing so in much smaller size than in the past -
both on the long and short side - as my conviction is simply not there. @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney

I tweeted this to @realdonaldtrump this past weekend: @DougKass @realDonaldTrump You unilaterally abandoned the Iran nuclear deal (over the objections of our allies and your security advisors) and despite Iran's adherence to the terms. In the interim you established no coherent

strategy to contain Iran. You imposed sanctions on Iran which failed to thwart Iran's mischief. You say the attack two days ago was based on imminent attacks planned against Americans (but fail to disclose what they are) and reports are that the evidence is "razor thin."

How are we to believe a President who lies so frequently and engages in improvisational policy? (Calling off strikes in Iran ten minutes beforehand, inviting Taliban to Camp David and abandoning the Kurds) Secretary Pompeo said on Fox that Americans are now safer.

We are clearly not as safe as a week ago. Iran will now, no doubt, revive its nuclear capability. A fragile global economic recovery is at risk as the energy infrastructure faces bona fide threats. You failed to notify our allies of the attack and have over time alienated those

allies - so we stand almost alone now. Iran will likely respond in multiple and unpredictable ways and places. You are playing 52 card pickup when a chess grandmaster is needed. @tomkeene @jimcramer @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @riskreversal @guyadami @business
